                <h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://usnewsnow.org/2016/02/matt-harvey-says-hed-consider-long-term-extension-to-stay-with-mets-2/" rel="bookmark" title="Matt Harvey says he’d consider long-term extension to stay with Mets">Matt Harvey says he’d consider long-term extension to stay with Mets</a></h1>
                <div class="td-module-meta-info">
	                                    <div class="td-post-author-name">By <a itemprop="author" href="http://usnewsnow.org/author/usnewsnow/">USNewsNow</a> - </div>                    <div class="td-post-date"><time  itemprop="dateCreated" class="entry-date updated td-module-date" datetime="2016-02-15T17:50:57+00:00" >February 15, 2016</time><meta itemprop="interactionCount" content="UserComments:0"/></div>                                    </div>

                <div class="td-post-featured-image"><a href="http://usnewsnow.org/2016/02/matt-harvey-says-hed-consider-long-term-extension-to-stay-with-mets-2/"><img width="635" height="412" itemprop="image" class="entry-thumb" src="http://i2.wp.com/usnewsnow.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/article-harvey-0215-1.jpeg?resize=635%2C412" alt="Matt Harvey says he’d consider long-term extension to stay with Mets" title="Matt Harvey says he’d consider long-term extension to stay with Mets"/></a></div>
	            <div class="td-post-text-content td-post-content">
		            <p id="mct_ai_excerpt"> Matt Harvey arrives at Mets camp and talks about the possibility of a long-term deal. PORT ST. LUCIE &mdash; Matt Harvey would consider an extension to stay with the Mets for awhile.</p>
<p>The ace righthander said Monday that despite talk that he is headed for free agency in 2018, he would consider a long-term deal to stay in New York. But after his first time negotiating his salary this past winter, he said he&#8217;s never been approached by the Mets about it.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve never shied away from it, I never said I wouldn&rsquo;t consider it,&rdquo; Harvey said. &ldquo;I haven&rsquo;t heard anything about that.&rdquo;</p>
<p> FIVE QUESTIONS FOR METS HEADING INTO SPRING TRAINING </p>
<p>Harvey is under Mets control, but on a negotiated year-to-year deal going forward until after the 2018 season. His agent Scott Boras also said this winter the Mets had never reached out to him about possibly buying out Harvey&rsquo;s arbitration or free agency years. Boras has a reputation of taking his clients to free agency and getting big-money contracts for them.</p>
<p>While Harvey has not been asked to look to his future with the Mets, he isn&rsquo;t looking back either. He spent enough time over the winter thinking about the slider he threw to Eric Hosmer in the ninth inning on Nov. 1 and he has learned from it. Harvey claimed that the Mets never discussed an extension with him, even though he would be open to one. But it&#8217;s now time for Harvey to move on and focus on 2016.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Obviously, if I went back, I&rsquo;d throw a different pitch,&rdquo; Harvey said the Hosmer at-bat that started the Royals&rsquo; rally to win Game 5 of the 2015 World Series. &ldquo;Everybody wishes they could go back at some point and change things.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am always going to want the ball as much as the next guy is,&rdquo; Harvey said of talking his way back into the game for the ninth inning. &quot;But we&rsquo;re excited to be back and to start the new year.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Harvey reported to the Mets&#8217; spring training complex Monday for voluntary workouts, two days before the team&rsquo;s pitchers and catchers are required to be in town. He said that certainly the Mets losing in five games to the Royals in the World Series &mdash; and his part in it &mdash; motivated him all offseason.</p>
<p> HARPER: PICTURING YANKS, METS AFTER 2019 FREE-AGENT CLASS </p>
<p>And while he knows that slider was a mistake, [&#8230;]</p>
<p id="mct-ai-attriblink"><a href="http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/mets/matt-harvey-long-term-deal-mets-article-1.2532056" >continue reading at www.nydailynews.com</a></p>
	            </div>
            </div>

            <meta itemprop="author" content = "USNewsNow"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2016-02-15T17:50:57+00:00"><meta itemprop="headline " content="Matt Harvey says he’d consider long-term extension to stay with Mets"><meta itemprop="image" content="http://i2.wp.com/usnewsnow.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/article-harvey-0215-1.jpeg?fit=635%2C412"><meta itemprop="interactionCount" content="UserComments:0"/>        </div>

        
        <div class="td_module_15 td-animation-stack post-18434 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-new-york tag-new tag-york" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Article">
            <div class="item-details">
                <h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://usnewsnow.org/2016/02/tasked-with-combating-opium-afghan-officials-depend-on-it-2/" rel="bookmark" title="Tasked With Combating Opium, Afghan Officials Depend on It">Tasked With Combating Opium, Afghan Officials Depend on It</a></h1>
                <div class="td-module-meta-info">
	                                    <div class="td-post-author-name">By <a itemprop="author" href="http://usnewsnow.org/author/usnewsnow/">USNewsNow</a> - </div>                    <div class="td-post-date"><time  itemprop="dateCreated" class="entry-date updated td-module-date" datetime="2016-02-15T17:50:57+00:00" >February 15, 2016</time><meta itemprop="interactionCount" content="UserComments:0"/></div>                                    </div>

                <div class="td-post-featured-image"><a href="http://usnewsnow.org/2016/02/tasked-with-combating-opium-afghan-officials-depend-on-it-2/"><img width="675" height="450" itemprop="image" class="entry-thumb" src="http://i1.wp.com/usnewsnow.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/narcostate-web-master675-1.jpeg?resize=675%2C450" alt="Tasked With Combating Opium, Afghan Officials Depend on It" title="Tasked With Combating Opium, Afghan Officials Depend on It"/></a></div>
	            <div class="td-post-text-content td-post-content">
		            <p id="mct_ai_excerpt"> Photo Afghan farmers harvested poppies last spring in the Nad Ali district of Helmand Province. Credit Bryan Denton for The New York Times GARMSIR, Afghanistan &mdash; The United States spent more than $7 billion in the past 14 years to fight the runaway poppy production that has made Afghan opium the world&rsquo;s biggest brand. Tens of billions more went to governance programs to stem corruption and train a credible police force. Countless more dollars and thousands of lives were lost on the main thrust of the war: to put the Afghan government in charge of district centers and to instill rule of law.</p>
<p>But here in one of the only corners of Helmand Province that is peaceful and in firm government control, the green stalks and swollen bulbs of opium were growing thick and high within eyeshot of official buildings during the past poppy season &mdash; signs of a local narco-state administered directly by government officials.</p>
<p>In the district of Garmsir, not only is poppy cultivation tolerated, the local government depends on it. Officials have imposed a tax on farmers practically identical to the one the Taliban uses in places they control. Some of the revenue is kicked up the chain, all the way to officials in Kabul, the capital, ensuring that the local authorities maintain support from higher-ups and keeping the opium growing. And Garmsir is just one example of official involvement in the drug trade.</p>
<p>Multiple visits to Afghan opium country over the past year, and extensive interviews with opium farmers, local elders, and Afghan and Western officials, laid bare the reality that even if the Western-backed government succeeds, the opium seems here to stay.</p>
<p>More than ever, Afghan government officials have become directly involved in the opium trade, expanding their competition with the Taliban beyond politics and into a struggle for control of the drug traffic and revenue. At the local level, the fight itself can often look like a turf war between drug gangs, even as American troops are being pulled back into the battle on the government&rsquo;s behalf, particularly in Helmand, in southern Afghanistan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There are phases of government complicity, starting with accommodation of the farmers and then on to cooperation with them,&rdquo; said David Mansfield, a researcher who conducted more than 15 years of fieldwork on Afghan opium. &ldquo;The last is predation, where the government essentially takes over the business entirely.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The huge boom in poppy production that began [&#8230;]</p>
<p id="mct-ai-attriblink"><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/16/world/asia/afghanistan-opium-heroin-taliban-helmand.html?_r=0" >continue reading at www.nytimes.com</a></p>
	            </div>
            </div>

            <meta itemprop="author" content = "USNewsNow"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2016-02-15T17:50:57+00:00"><meta itemprop="headline " content="Tasked With Combating Opium, Afghan Officials Depend on It"><meta itemprop="image" content="http://i1.wp.com/usnewsnow.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/narcostate-web-master675-1.jpeg?fit=675%2C450"><meta itemprop="interactionCount" content="UserComments:0"/>        </div>

        
        <div class="td_module_15 td-animation-stack post-18432 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-new-york tag-city tag-new tag-york" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Article">
            <div class="item-details">
                <h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://usnewsnow.org/2016/02/schumer-criticizes-cut-on-anti-terrorism-spending-in-2017-budget-seeks-increase-2/" rel="bookmark" title="Schumer Criticizes Cut on Anti-Terrorism Spending in 2017 Budget, Seeks Increase">Schumer Criticizes Cut on Anti-Terrorism Spending in 2017 Budget, Seeks Increase</a></h1>
                <div class="td-module-meta-info">
	                                    <div class="td-post-author-name">By <a itemprop="author" href="http://usnewsnow.org/author/usnewsnow/">USNewsNow</a> - </div>                    <div class="td-post-date"><time  itemprop="dateCreated" class="entry-date updated td-module-date" datetime="2016-02-15T17:50:53+00:00" >February 15, 2016</time><meta itemprop="interactionCount" content="UserComments:0"/></div>                                    </div>

                <div class="td-post-featured-image"><a href="http://usnewsnow.org/2016/02/schumer-criticizes-cut-on-anti-terrorism-spending-in-2017-budget-seeks-increase-2/"><img width="333" height="281" itemprop="image" class="entry-thumb" src="http://i2.wp.com/usnewsnow.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/zWzgRP4C-333x281-1.jpeg?resize=333%2C281" alt="Schumer Criticizes Cut on Anti-Terrorism Spending in 2017 Budget, Seeks Increase" title="Schumer Criticizes Cut on Anti-Terrorism Spending in 2017 Budget, Seeks Increase"/></a></div>
	            <div class="td-post-text-content td-post-content">
		            <p id="mct_ai_excerpt"> Photo Courtesy of Charles Schumer via Twitter account Amy Schumer isn&rsquo;t the only one with a sharp tongue.</p>
<p>After the White House recently released proposed budget cuts for anti-terror spending, her cousin, Charles Schumer, the Democratic senator from New York, said that the new cuts would be ill-advised and has vowed to fight for an increase in anti-terror spending for New York.</p>
<p>The Urban Area Security Initiative (UASI) is the program that was recommended for $330 million in funding for 2017, as opposed to $600 million in funding in 2016. New York relies on the UASI to maintain response infrastructure and for terrorism prevention. To cut spending would be to potentially alter that infrastructure, according to Schumer.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In light of recent attacks in Paris and San Bernardino, and the vow by our extremist enemies to launch more attacks on our shores, it makes no sense for bureaucrats in Washington to propose cuts to vital terror-prevention programs like UASI,&rdquo; Schumer said in a press release.&ldquo;New York City remains terror target #1 and the NYPD relies on these programs to keep us safe &mdash; something they have done a very good job of since 9-11.&rdquo;</p>
<p>New York City receives $180 million of anti-terrorism spending, which is used for training the NYPD and the New York City Fire Department.</p>
<p>The U.S. government released the 2017 budget last week.</p>
