                <h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://usnewsnow.org/2016/02/can-the-souths-love-affair-with-a-new-york-yankee-last/" rel="bookmark" title="Can the South’s Love Affair With a New York Yankee Last?">Can the South’s Love Affair With a New York Yankee Last?</a></h1>
                <div class="td-module-meta-info">
	                                    <div class="td-post-author-name">By <a itemprop="author" href="http://usnewsnow.org/author/usnewsnow/">USNewsNow</a> - </div>                    <div class="td-post-date"><time  itemprop="dateCreated" class="entry-date updated td-module-date" datetime="2016-02-15T17:50:51+00:00" >February 15, 2016</time><meta itemprop="interactionCount" content="UserComments:0"/></div>                                    </div>

                <div class="td-post-featured-image"><a href="http://usnewsnow.org/2016/02/can-the-souths-love-affair-with-a-new-york-yankee-last/"><img width="696" height="377" itemprop="image" class="entry-thumb" src="http://usnewsnow.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/jpeg-4-696x377." alt="Can the South’s Love Affair With a New York Yankee Last?" title="Can the South’s Love Affair With a New York Yankee Last?"/></a></div>
	            <div class="td-post-text-content td-post-content">
		            <p id="mct_ai_excerpt"> Getty BATON ROUGE, La. &mdash; Some 10,000 fans waited at least an hour in line late last week to fill an arena here along the Mississippi River. And when the star attraction &ndash; Donald Trump &ndash; entered from behind a blue curtain, the roar was so piercing, the stomping so loud, you would have thought that a LSU player had just hit a game-winning basket. But Trump was here to talk about another kind of winning: his easy-to-grasp, sports-arena portrayal of an America that doesn&rsquo;t &ldquo;beat anybody anymore.&rdquo; First stop, just south of the border.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who&rsquo;s going to pay for the wall?&rdquo; he called out. &ldquo;Mexico!&rdquo; the crowd shouted as one.</p>
<p>Fresh off his huge win in New Hampshire, Trump is taking his angry populist message to the South, the next political battleground and a region where recent surveys have him leading by 10 or more points nearly everywhere. But Trump&rsquo;s somewhat defensive performance in the rancorous GOP debate in South Carolina Saturday night&mdash;punctuated by the crowd&rsquo;s boos, especially over his attacks on President George W. Bush, who is still popular there&mdash;could create an opening for his rivals in the South. Jeb Bush, who turned in perhaps his strongest performance yet, is certainly banking on that in the South Carolina primary on Feb. 20, and he can count on the history of that state supporting his father and brother going back 25 years. (&ldquo;I&rsquo;m sick and tired of [Trump] going after my family,&rdquo; Bush said Saturday to cheers.)</p>
<p>Marco Rubio, the senator from Florida, is presenting himself as the candidate who has the foreign policy chops in a region that favors a strong military. John Kasich, the governor of Ohio, is appealing to moderates and is hoping that publicity following his second place finish in New Hampshire will bring the political oxygen his cash-starved campaign needs.</p>
<p>Ted Cruz, the Texas senator, handily bested Trump in the Iowa caucuses with an impressive ground game that appeared to open daylight between Trump and the base followers he&rsquo;s trying to win over&mdash;in particular the evangelicals and social conservatives who are so plentiful in the South. That&rsquo;s why Tony Perkins, a former state legislator from Louisiana who heads the Family Research Council, believes that the Iowa Caucus results promise more of the same for Cruz throughout the South and in Texas, which holds its delegate-rich primary on March 1. Cruz has led polls in Texas.</p>
<p>In South Carolina, [&#8230;]</p>
<p id="mct-ai-attriblink"><a href="http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/02/south-love-affair-louisiana-letter-yankee-213632" >continue reading at www.politico.com</a></p>
	            </div>
            </div>

